x4freetext: tantalum backings by electron bombardment of isotopic
boron powder placed into a tantalum crucible. A
carbon impurity of less than 1.2% did not present a
problem because its neutron energies from the
13C(alpha,n) reaction never coincided with those from
11B(alpha,n) and the neutron intensity was very weak.
For measurements below 6.7 MeV a 22 microg/cm2 target
was normally used and above this energy a 53
microg/cm2 target. This resulted in alpha-energy
spreads of 18.5 keV at Ealpha = 4 MeV and of 32 keV
at Ealpha = 7 MeV. For the two very narrow resonances
just below Ealpha = 3 MeV additional targets as thin
A proton recoil detector, consisting of a

The neutron yields and cross sections were
derived from neutron spectra measured with a proton
Author: Analysis of the shown in Fig.1 neutron
groups suggests that the n0 neutron group corresponds
to the ground state in 14N and the n1 group
corresponds to the excitation of 2312.798 keV state.
Beyond that we assume that scale of stilbene
scintillator was not linear and assign n2 and n3
groups to 3948.10 and 5105.89 keV states, respectively.
